MEDIUM|internal/tdmigrate/validate.go:22|DecodeShardStrict calls dec.Decode exactly once, so a shard file containing a second YAML document (a `---` separator produced by an accidental concatenation or bad merge) decodes only the first document and silently discards the rest with a nil error. This is a hole in the strict-load gate that AC4 promises will fail loudly on malformed input.|After the first successful Decode, call dec.Decode(&throwaway) again and require it to return io.EOF; any other result (nil or parse error) means trailing content and must be a hard error. Add a fixture with a two-document shard.|correctness|30|internal/tdmigrate/validate.go:18-29|claude
MEDIUM|internal/tdmigrate/validate.go:45|ValidateDir and LoadShards locate shards with filepath.Glob, which returns (nil, nil) for a directory that does not exist (Glob only errors on a malformed pattern). So `td-migrate validate --items /typo/path` returns exit 0 with "0 shard(s) OK" — the validation gate silently reports success when pointed at a wrong, unmounted, or pre-migration directory.|Stat the directory and hard-error if it is missing; optionally return a sentinel error when zero shard files are found so the caller decides whether emptiness is acceptable rather than treating no-files as all-valid.|error-handling|30|internal/tdmigrate/validate.go:44-65|claude
MEDIUM|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:67|splitRow splits a table row on every pipe with no pipe-escaping. The writer side (generate.go cell) sanitizes pipe to slash so machine output is safe, but a hand-edited README row that contains a literal pipe inside Problem/Fix adds phantom cells; if the cell count happens to land on 9 or 11 the row is silently re-interpreted (a 9-column row with two stray pipes parses as an 11-column reconciled row, mapping Problem text into Reviewers/Confidence) — silent corruption instead of the mandated loud failure.|Detect and reject unbalanced or unescaped pipes (or unescape backslash-pipe before splitting) and hard-error on an inconsistent raw pipe count. Add a fixture: a 9-column row whose Problem contains a literal pipe must error, not parse to 11 cells.|correctness|60|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:62-72|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:41|driftHeader only catches a drifted provenance header that contains a colon (regex `From ([^:]+):`). A colonless drifted header such as `### [2026-01-01] From Standup` matches neither sectionHeader nor driftHeader, falls through without resetting cur, and every item beneath it is silently re-attributed to the PREVIOUS shard (wrong date/label/source) while still passing Shard.Validate.|Broaden the drift guard to fire on any `^### \[\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}\] From ` line that sectionHeader did not match, regardless of colon, and hard-error. Add a colonless-header fixture asserting a loud failure.|error-handling|60|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:36-47|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:45|The in-section row gate skips any line that does not start with a leading pipe after trimming. GitHub-Flavored Markdown permits tables without leading pipes, and a hand edit can drop one, so a genuine data row is silently dropped with no loud failure — a zero-data-loss gap the epic forbids.|Inside an active section, route a line carrying the expected number of internal pipe separators but lacking a leading pipe through rowToItem, or hard-error on the ambiguous line rather than silently skipping it.|correctness|30|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:45-47|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:28|flush() discards any section with zero items with no diagnostic. If a recognized section header's rows all fail the pipe gate (formatting drift), the entire provenance section vanishes silently, contradicting the function's own zero-data-loss claim.|When a section header was seen but produced zero parseable items, emit a hard error (or at minimum a stderr warning) instead of silently dropping the section.|error-handling|30|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:28-33|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:93|Column semantics are encoded as bare positional indices (cells[0]..cells[10]) with magic 9/11 counts and a hardcoded "Group" header sentinel, and the same column layout is independently re-encoded in generate.go. There is no shared schema constant tying reader and writer together, so a future column insertion in one file silently desynchronizes the round-trip — the exact silent-corruption class this epic exists to eliminate.|Introduce shared column-order/count constants consumed by both parse.go and generate.go, and add a round-trip test that fails if either side's column order changes independently.|maintainability|60|internal/tdmigrate/parse.go:74-122|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/shard.go:37|ShardFilename interpolates s.Date raw into the filename while only the Label is slug-sanitized, and Shard.Validate checks only that Date is non-empty, never the documented YYYY-MM-DD format. Reaching this via migrate is safe because ParseREADME regex-constrains the date, but a hand-authored or merge-corrupted shard whose date contains path separators would compose a directory-escaping path and still pass Validate.|Enforce the `^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}$` format in Shard.Validate and reject any composed filename containing a path separator before WriteShards uses it.|security|30|internal/tdmigrate/shard.go:37-44|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/generate.go:13|GenerateTable's docstring claims per-item data is "preserved verbatim" and the regenerated parse is "semantically equal" to the original, but cell() rewrites pipe to slash and newlines to spaces, so table to table is intentionally lossy (the parse_test fixture "a / b / c" demonstrates it). The claim holds only at the shard layer and will mislead a maintainer who relies on table-level round-trip equality for a diff or verification step.|Correct the GenerateTable docstring to state that round-trip equality holds at the shard layer only and the regenerated table is a deliberately lossy single-line summary; SCHEMA.md already documents this correctly.|maintainability|15|internal/tdmigrate/generate.go:10-14|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/run.go:65|Subcommand-level help (`td-migrate migrate -h`) returns flag.ErrHelp from fs.Parse, which the code treats as a generic parse error and returns exit 2 with the usage text on stderr — inconsistent with the top-level `help`/`-h` handler that returns exit 0 to stdout.|After fs.Parse, special-case errors.Is(err, flag.ErrHelp) to return 0 (and route help text to stdout). The fix applies to all three subcommands.|maintainability|15|internal/tdmigrate/run.go:65-66,103-104,122-123|claude
LOW|internal/tdmigrate/run.go:54|newFlags(name, args, stderr) accepts an args parameter it never uses; every caller passes args and then separately calls fs.Parse(args). The dead parameter implies newFlags performs the parse (it does not), inviting a future bug where a caller reads the flag value before Parse has run and silently gets the default.|Drop the unused args parameter from newFlags; parsing already lives correctly in each caller.|maintainability|5|internal/tdmigrate/run.go:54-60|claude
